Optimized Sol:

from typing import List

class Solution:
    def maximumSubarraySum(self, nums: List[int], k: int) -> int:
        if len(nums) < k:
            return 0
        
        max_sum = 0
        current_sum = 0
        freq = {}
        
        # Step 1: Build first window of size k
        for i in range(k):
            current_sum += nums[i]
            
            # Basic way to count frequency
            if nums[i] in freq:
                freq[nums[i]] += 1
            else:
                freq[nums[i]] = 1
        
        # Check if first window has all distinct elements
        if len(freq) == k:
            max_sum = current_sum
        
        # Step 2: Slide the window
        for i in range(k, len(nums)):
            # Add new element
            current_sum += nums[i]
            if nums[i] in freq:
                freq[nums[i]] += 1
            else:
                freq[nums[i]] = 1
            
            # Remove left element (out of window)
            left = nums[i - k]
            freq[left] -= 1
            if freq[left] == 0:
                del freq[left]          # Remove from dictionary if count becomes 0
            current_sum -= left

            # If current window has exactly k distinct numbers
            if len(freq) == k:
                max_sum = max(max_sum, current_sum)
        
        return max_sum
Time & Space Complexity: HashMap vs Set
This is the core reason we prefer HashMap in the optimized solution.

Important Clarification First
Individually, both have the same average complexity:

Operation	Set	HashMap/Dict
Insert	O(1)	O(1)
Delete	O(1)	O(1)
Lookup	O(1)	O(1)
The difference is NOT in the data structure itself.
The difference is in HOW we use them.

